f that helps. The existing test suite might require more resources due to downstream dependencies. Increasing the max heap could be justified. Using a setting like `forkEvery = 1` could help prevent heap accumulation since it seems related to KafkaClientsTest. It’s worth testing these adjustments to see if they resolve the issue.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Investigating memory issues**\\n\\nI’m considering if there’s a memory leak in KafkaClientsTest since setting maxHeap to 1GB still resulted in an OOM error after two classes. Maybe using `forkEvery = 1` could help isolate tests, but I'm curious why the baseline test didn’t fail. It could be that prior tests left some memory or cache. The extra KafkaFutureTest class might have contributed to memory issues when running all tests. Forking for each class could add overhead, but it might be worthwhile given the number of classes tested. Setting this only for JVM tests could be a good alternative.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Adjusting fork settings**\\n\\nI’m considering adjusting the `forkEvery` setting to either 1 or 5. However, for the native image tests, there’s only one binary that may not be relevant here. Since the user is still experiencing errors with heap memory, I think adding `forkEvery` might help, along with increasing the maxHeapSize. If I set `forkEvery` to 1, each worker would get 1GB, which should pass. But I wonder if the Gradle test worker forks for each class and whether dynamic instrumentation is contributing to the OOM issue.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_j38Zq5rOvIl9B9iHtQqwsXwt|fc_099e365a07fc752c016a0f5a40af088192b747a316b72d782b", "name": "edit", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/org.apache.kafka/kafka-clients/4.2.0/build.gradle", "edits": [{"oldText": "tasks.withType(Test).configureEach {\n    maxHeapSize = '1g'\n    jvmArgs += ['--add-exports=java.security.jgss/sun.security.krb5=ALL-UNNAMED']\n    systemProperty 'java.vendor', 'IBM Corporation'\n}\n",